{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17624725","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17624725"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:20:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:20:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16956"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16956","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16956"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0,0,0.24,0.51]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9646"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68672"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9646","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9646"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16956"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54129"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9850"},{"type":"tags","id":"9853"},{"type":"tags","id":"10290"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22755"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22760"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68672","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68672"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe sinoatrial node serves as the primary pacemaker of the heart, generating regular electrical impulses that initiate each cardiac cycle.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism responsible for spontaneous depolarization in the sinoatrial node?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fast inward calcium current through L-type channels","Sodium-potassium pump activation","Rapid outward potassium current","Rapid inward sodium current through voltage-gated channels","Slow inward sodium \u0027funny\u0027 current"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eslow inward sodium current through funny channels\u003C/strong\u003E (also called HCN channels) is responsible for the gradual depolarization during phase 4 of the sinoatrial node action potential. This pacemaker potential brings the membrane potential to threshold, triggering an action potential.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERapid outward potassium current\u003C/strong\u003E - This would cause hyperpolarization rather than depolarization\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFast inward calcium current through L-type channels\u003C/strong\u003E - While L-type calcium channels contribute to the action potential upstroke, they are not responsible for the initial spontaneous depolarization\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESodium-potassium pump activation\u003C/strong\u003E - The sodium-potassium pump generates an outward current that would oppose depolarization\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERapid inward sodium current through voltage-gated channels\u003C/strong\u003E - Unlike working myocardium, sinoatrial node cells do not have fast sodium channels\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe funny channels open when the membrane potential is negative (during hyperpolarization) and allow sodium to slowly enter the cell, gradually bringing it to threshold. This unique property enables the sinoatrial node to function as the heart\u0027s natural pacemaker.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The sinoatrial node generates action potentials spontaneously due to a gradual depolarization during phase 4 called the pacemaker potential.","The pacemaker potential in sinoatrial node cells is primarily driven by a slow inward sodium current through funny channels.","The sinoatrial node has the fastest intrinsic rate of spontaneous depolarization compared to other cardiac pacemaker tissues."],"references":["Boron W. F., Boulpaep E. L. Medical Physiology. (3rd edition). US. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2017."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54129"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16956"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54129","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54129"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T09:58:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T09:58:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9646"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68672"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading"